# What changed in .NET 9 and later

This is the key point for your presentation.

## Before .NET 9

The OpenTelemetry runtime instrumentation package collected many runtime metrics by calling .NET runtime APIs directly, for example:

| Area                     | Example API used                  |
| ------------------------ | --------------------------------- |
| GC collections           | `GC.CollectionCount(...)`         |
| Total allocated bytes    | `GC.GetTotalAllocatedBytes()`     |
| GC memory info           | `GC.GetGCMemoryInfo()`            |
| Thread pool count        | `ThreadPool.ThreadCount`          |
| Thread pool queue length | `ThreadPool.PendingWorkItemCount` |
| Lock contention          | `Monitor.LockContentionCount`     |
| Active timers            | `Timer.ActiveCount`               |
| First chance exceptions  | `AppDomain.FirstChanceException`  |

The OpenTelemetry runtime instrumentation README lists many of these APIs directly. ([GitHub][2])

## .NET 9+

.NET 9 introduced built-in runtime metrics through the **`System.Runtime` meter**. The OpenTelemetry runtime instrumentation package says that when an app targets **.NET 9 or greater**, the package registers a `Meter` to receive the built-in `System.Runtime` metrics instead of recreating those runtime measurements itself. ([NuGet][3])

Microsoft’s runtime metrics documentation says the `System.Runtime` meter reports measurements from **GC, JIT, AssemblyLoader, ThreadPool, exception handling, CPU, and memory**, and that these metrics are available automatically for all .NET apps. ([Microsoft Learn][4])

So the clean presentation statement is:

> **In .NET 9 and later, the runtime itself publishes many of these measurements through the built-in `System.Runtime` meter. The OpenTelemetry runtime instrumentation library listens to that meter and exports the measurements using OpenTelemetry conventions.**

For .NET 10, I would simply say:

> **.NET 10 continues the modern `System.Diagnostics.Metrics` model. The big runtime-metrics shift happened in .NET 9, where built-in runtime metrics were added to the `System.Runtime` meter.**

I would avoid saying “.NET 10 introduced this” unless you are referring to a specific .NET 10 feature.

