This is where runtime metrics help. After the deployment, we can see process memory increasing, allocation-related metrics trending upward, and GC collections becoming more frequent. If GC pause time or thread pool queue length also increases, that gives us stronger evidence that the .NET service itself is under runtime pressure.

So the conclusion is not simply “the backend is slow.” The better conclusion is: after this deployment, this service appears to be allocating more memory, causing more GC activity and possible thread pool backlog, which is contributing to higher request latency.

That is the value of enabling runtime metrics through the library. It gives teams a lightweight way to correlate traces with runtime health signals and quickly separate downstream slowness from application runtime pressure.

